se gases]]\n[[Category:Household chemicals]]\n[[Category:Inorganic solvents]]\n[[Category:Laser gain media]]\n[[Category:Nuclear reactor coolants]]\n[[Category:Oxocarbons]]\n[[Category:Propellants]]\n[[Category:Refrigerants]]\n[[Category:Gaseous signaling molecules]]\n[[Category:Heterocumulenes]]\n[[Category:E-number additives]]\n", "name_user": "42.60.53.43", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBackground)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_dioxide"}
{"title_page": "Christopher Plummer filmography", "text_new": "{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Plummer}}\n[[File:Christopher Plummer 1964.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Plummer in 1964]]\n[[Christopher Plummer]] (born December 13, 1929) is a [[Cinema of Canada|Canadian]] film, television and stage actor. On stage, Plummer's most notable roles are that of Cyrano de Bergerac in ''[[Cyrano (musical)|Cyrano]]'' (1974) and as [[John Barrymore]] in ''[[Barrymore (play)|Barrymore]]''. He won the [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play]] for these two roles. On film, Plummer is known for portraying [[Georg von Trapp|Captain von Trapp]] in ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'' (1965).<ref name=\"Plummer\">{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2010/01/31/at_80_christopher_plummer_lands_roles_that_are_his_cup_of_tea/?page=all| title=At 80, Plummer has arrived at his 'Station'| work=The Boston Globe | date=January 31, 2010| author=Judy Abel| accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> He also appeared in ''[[Waterloo (1970 film)|Waterloo]]'' (1970), ''[[The Man Who Would Be King (film)|The Man Who Would Be King]]'' (1975), ''[[The Insider (film)|The Insider]]'' (1999), as [[Leo Tolstoy]] in ''[[The Last Station]]'' (2009) and as [[J. Paul Getty]] in ''[[All the Money in the World]]'' (2017).\n\nPlummer provided the voice of antagonist Charles F. Muntz in the [[Pixar]] animated film ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'' (2009).<ref name=time>{{cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|title=Up, Up and Away: Another New High for Pixar|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1896737,00.html|accessdate=November 22, 2013|newspaper=Time|date=May 28, 2009|authorlink=Richard Corliss}}</ref>\n\nPlummer won an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his performance in [[Mike Mills (director)|Mike Mills]]' film ''[[Beginners]]'' (2010).\n\n==Performances==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1958\n| ''[[Stage Struck (1958 film)|Stage Struck]]''\n| Joe Sheridan\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Wind Across the Everglades]]''\n| Walt Murdock\n|\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]''\n| [[Commodus]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1965\n| ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]''\n| [[Georg von Trapp|Captain Georg von Trapp]]\n|-\n| ''[[Inside Daisy Clover]]''\n| Raymond Swan\n|\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Triple Cross (1966 film)|Triple Cross]]''\n| [[Eddie Chapman]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1967\n| ''[[The Night of the Generals]]''\n| Field Marshal [[Erwin Rommel]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Oedipus the King (1968 film)|Oedipus the King]]''\n| [[Oedipus]]\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Nobody Runs Forever]]''\n| Sir James Quentin\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1969\n| ''[[Battle of Britain (film)|Battle of Britain]]''\n| Squadron Leader Colin Harvey\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Royal Hunt of the Sun (film)|The Royal Hunt of the Sun]]''\n| [[Atahualpa]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Lock Up Your Daughters (1969 film)|Lock Up Your Daughters!]]''\n| Lord Foppington\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Waterloo (1970 film)|Waterloo]]''\n| [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]]\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[The Pyx]]''\n| Det. Sgt. Jim Henderson\n|\n|-\n|1974\n| ''[[The Happy Prince (1974 film)|The Happy Prince]]''\n| The Happy Prince\n|[[Short film]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1975\n| ''[[The Spiral Staircase (1975 film)|The Spiral Staircase]]''\n| Dr. Joe Sherman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Return of the Pink Panther]]''\n| Sir Charles Litton\n|\n|-\n|[[Conduct Unbecoming (1975 film)|''Conduct Unbecoming'']]\n| Major Alastair Wimbourne\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Man Who Would Be King (film)|The Man Who Would Be King]]''\n| [[Rudyard Kipling]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Day That Shook the World]]''\n| [[Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria|Archduke Ferdinand of Austria]]\n|\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Aces High (film)|Aces High]]''\n| Captain 'Uncle' Sinclair\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1977\n| ''[[The Assignment (1977